--- Matt Munz &lt;matt@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Hi all,
&gt; 
&gt;     I&#39;ve been using assertEquals (Junit v3.5) in many tests and it
&gt; works well.  I&#39;ve been thinking that it might be handy to have
&gt; assertGreater() and assertGreaterOrEqual() methods as well.  My first
&gt; impulse is to subclass Assert and put them there.  Is there another
&gt; (better) way to do this? Any ideas would be appreciated.  If anyone
&gt; has done this before and would like to send me their code, that would
&gt; be appreciated too ;)
&gt; 

Just a thought... 

Rather than using inheritance, you could define binary methods
(functors) that are then used by the canonical assertion methods of the
Assert class, as in

    public class AssertRange {
        public static boolean greaterThanOrEqual(int a, int b) {
            return a &gt;= b;
        }
        public static boolean lessThanOrEqual(int a, int b) {
            return a &lt;= b;
        }
    }

    public void testSomething() {
        assert(&quot;Test something&quot;, 
            AssertRange.greaterThanOrEquals(9, 10));
    }

This may help promote pluggability of assertion behavior.

The other option would be to use composition rather than inheritance. 
The AssertRange could delegate to the Assert class.

Mike

